          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:16px !important">What is a frozen conflict?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-3-3.jpg" alt="What is a frozen conflict?" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">A frozen conflict is when active fighting has ceased, but no formal peace agreement or resolution has been reached, leaving the conflict unresolved. It is also called a prolonged stalemate, where neither side achieves a decisive victory. Frozen conflicts often involve territorial or political disagreements, with occasional flare-ups of violence but without full-scale war.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Unrecognized entities or states may exist in frozen conflicts, with breakaway regions or territories controlling areas but lacking international recognition. External powers often support one side or both, reinforcing the status quo. In some cases, all parties prefer the status quo. Despite no active conflict, the lack of a comprehensive peace deal leaves underlying issues unresolved, which can cause ongoing humanitarian and economic challenges for affected populations.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Examples include the <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-66852070" target="_blank">Nagorno-Karabakh conflict</a>, <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-18284837" target="_blank">Transnistria</a>, South Ossetia, and Abkhazia. These frozen conflicts persist because of deeply entrenched political positions, a lack of international consensus, and external interests that prevent resolution.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
